224
00:18:25,220 --> 00:18:36,220
And I remember one time Emil showed me, he was a bit embarrassed about it, because it's not something that has a lot of objective value.

225
00:18:36,220 --> 00:18:46,220
But he knew I would be interested in his autograph book, which he had maintained as a kid in his grandmother's salon,

226
00:18:46,220 --> 00:18:53,220
and had signatures in this book from Sigmund Floyd and a number of other very famous people, musicians and scientists.

227
00:18:53,220 --> 00:19:00,220
I can't recall exactly who now, but it was pretty impressive to see at the time.

228
00:19:00,220 --> 00:19:04,220
Was he a clunker of art?

229
00:19:04,220 --> 00:19:13,220
I don't think he had the financial wherewithal to collect art, but he had had art that he inherited from the family.

230
00:19:13,220 --> 00:19:21,220
And Emil's family was Jewish and had lived in both Austria, Vienna and France.

231
00:19:21,220 --> 00:19:33,220
And during the Nazi occupation and Nazi infiltration of countries in Europe, his family was forced to flee and often fled without their possession.

232
00:19:33,220 --> 00:19:44,220
So I know many years later he showed me a catalog of German art and architecture in which his parents' chairs were featured.

233
00:19:44,220 --> 00:19:53,220
And these were chairs that were part of the old Zupacondle home that they'd been forced to abandon when the Nazis arrived.

234
00:19:53,220 --> 00:20:01,220
And he had remnants of some art that he'd been able to take with him, Gustav Klimt, a triptitch and things like that,

235
00:20:01,220 --> 00:20:11,220
which I think he'd given away actually at that time. But he did have some art and some books that managed to survive that ugly process in Europe.

236
00:20:11,220 --> 00:20:21,220
Okay, well I want to talk now about art Robinson. And then basically, first of all, annoyingly as a scientist wasn't you initially met in the interaction with him?

237
00:20:22,220 --> 00:20:31,220
Yeah, that's a good question. I would say that I did not have enough science acumen at that time to offer any judgment on art Robinson.

238
00:20:31,220 --> 00:20:41,220
I knew that he was working very closely with Linus Polling, so I assume that he must be brilliant because I doubted that Linus Polling would tolerate fools.

239
00:20:41,220 --> 00:21:01,220
And research was clearly the most important thing in Pauling's life, research and science. And I just imagined that art Robinson must be a terrifically intelligent person to be working with Linus Polling because otherwise he wouldn't be at the institute.

240
00:21:01,220 --> 00:21:15,220
He seemed to have Polling's trust and many people had pretty high regard for art Robinson, called him kind of the boy wonder. He was quite young at that time as well. Maybe in his 30s I believe when he was president and director of the institute.

241
00:21:15,220 --> 00:21:42,220
He came up from UCSD to take a position in Polling's lab at Stanford and then together with Kendim at Co-Found at the institute, while the institute was still located at Stanford and then when they were able to secure a rental site in this building on Sandhill Road then they moved physically the institute and transferred the grants to the Sandhill Road location.

242
00:21:42,220 --> 00:22:02,220
I had a very favorable impression of art. I liked him quite a lot and he seemed to be incredibly driven. I didn't know at that time anything about his politics, his religion or anything. I never asked him about those things, I never talked to him about those things. It was all strictly science.

243
00:22:02,220 --> 00:22:18,220
I really enjoyed my interactions with him at that time. I was not high enough up in the food chain, the bureaucracy within the institute to really understand at the time the nature of the conflict that developed between art Robinson and Linus Polling.

244
00:22:18,220 --> 00:22:42,220
I was completely in the dark as to why that developed and why art left the institute. There was a series of very bewildering memos at that time. I remember after art left and of course there was gossip about what was going on and who was in charge and what had happened and so forth.

245
00:22:42,220 --> 00:23:06,220
I can't really remember the gossip very clearly but I do remember coming into my office one day and finding a memo from Linus Polling, a couple of short paragraphs explaining that art Robinson and absented himself from the institute and was no longer serving as the president director of Linus Polling was taking over that position and I should ignore directives from art Robinson.

246
00:23:06,220 --> 00:23:21,220
That was followed the next day by a memo from art Robinson to the effect that Linus Polling had no authority to remove him from his position and I should disregard the earlier memo from Linus Polling and things like that went back and forth for a while.

247
00:23:21,220 --> 00:23:50,220
So it was a period of tension to say the least at the institute people were a little bewildered as to what to do but I think ultimately because Linus Polling was chairman of the board and the institute was named for him and I think people just inferred that Linus Polling was in charge and therefore Linus Polling was the one who had the authority of say on what the status of art Robinson was at that time.

248
00:23:51,220 --> 00:23:57,220
So what do you think about Robinson as a personality in Tenskies and Fee or the Dump of the Line?

249
00:23:57,220 --> 00:24:01,220
Yes, he was very intense, very driven, no question about that.

250
00:24:01,220 --> 00:24:04,220
Any other adjectives that would suit you?

251
00:24:04,220 --> 00:24:20,220
Well, he had a very robust family life. I mean he was very, his wife Laura Lee Robinson at the time was working at the institute in the data acquisition and analysis from the metabolic profiling program.

252
00:24:20,220 --> 00:24:25,220
So she was there quite often, she was a very lovely person I liked her very much as well.

253
00:24:25,220 --> 00:24:30,220
And together they seemed like a very good pair, very happy married couple.

254
00:24:30,220 --> 00:24:42,220
It was quite a shock when she died so suddenly and Art of course had small children that he had to turn his attention to and to raise and it just seemed like a very stressful time for everyone.

255
00:24:42,220 --> 00:24:57,220
The combination of Laura Lee's very abrupt death, Art having his young kids to take care of now and also having this problem of Linus Polling and essentially losing his job at the institute.

256
00:24:57,220 --> 00:25:11,220
I do remember that prior to the schism with Linus Polling there had been several meetings in the institute's library about the future of the institute.

257
00:25:11,220 --> 00:25:20,220
And the prospect of moving to Oregon had been raised by Art Robinson specifically at that time.

258
00:25:20,220 --> 00:25:39,220
The late 1970s, Art had talked about property in Oregon and if my memory serves me I think it was near Eugene or Junction City that might be available at low cost for the institute to buy and build a building and set up laboratories there.

259
00:25:40,220 --> 00:25:53,220
And I think that there was an informal poll taken among staff as to who might be interested in relocating to Oregon at that time. Not many people were.

260
00:25:53,220 --> 00:25:57,220
Do you know anything more about where this idea came from on Oregon?

261
00:25:57,220 --> 00:26:02,220
I don't.

262
00:26:02,220 --> 00:26:26,220
Well, I should say also that when the schism between Polling and Art developed, it occurred to me that that might have been one of the factors that led to this problem because Polling of course had a very close relationship with friends and faculty at Stanford still, hard McConnell, Henry Taub, a number of other people in the chemistry department there and elsewhere.

263
00:26:26,220 --> 00:26:38,220
He had homes in Portola Valley and Big Sur and it didn't seem to me that he would want at his age and station and life to move to Oregon.

264
00:26:38,220 --> 00:26:46,220
And I was never at that time I wondered whether that was part of the problem that had developed between them.

265
00:26:46,220 --> 00:26:52,220
So in hindsight, do you have any other thoughts on what life was given?

266
00:26:52,220 --> 00:27:10,220
Well, when I became Chief Executive Officer or Executive Officer in the Linus Plains Institute in the early 1990s, I was talking about the institute before lots of groups quite often.

267
00:27:10,220 --> 00:27:18,220
And consequently, I had to familiarize myself pretty quickly with the history of the institute and some of the major figures in the institute.

268
00:27:18,220 --> 00:27:25,220
So I really had to learn a lot more about Linus Polling, his career than I previously had known.

269
00:27:25,220 --> 00:27:33,220
And I had to learn about Art Robinson and some of the activities that had transpired at the institute over the years.

270
00:27:33,220 --> 00:27:51,220
So I looked at some of the depositions, I looked at the court papers that were now available to me as Executive Officer and I read that material quite carefully at the time because I wanted to be able to represent the story accurately and to the best of my ability.

271
00:27:51,220 --> 00:28:00,220
So I thought it was incumbent upon me to learn as much as I could about that problem that developed between Robinson and Polling so that I would have a good understanding of it.

272
00:28:00,220 --> 00:28:12,220
And I wouldn't be simply mousing some person's opinion of what had happened but I had actually formed an opinion myself based on original research into the raw data, if you will.

273
00:28:12,220 --> 00:28:19,220
And that led me to the conclusion that there were administrative problems that had developed between Robinson and Polling.

274
00:28:19,220 --> 00:28:31,220
It didn't have anything to do with the results from the vitamin C and skin cancer experiments as far as I could tell as Art Robinson portrayed the whole problem.

275
00:28:31,220 --> 00:28:46,220
Art said that the anomalous results at low dose supplemental vitamin C that actually resulted in increased number of tumors in these hairless mice exposed to ultraviolet light.

276
00:28:46,220 --> 00:29:06,220
If you extrapolated that to people, it would be at risk for developing cancer, let's say skin cancer in this case, at the doses of supplementary vitamin C that Polling was recommending for good health.

277
00:29:06,220 --> 00:29:28,220
But there was a significant problem in that argument and the problem is that mice synthesize vitamin C. And I believe even Art himself at the time had suggested that the exogenous vitamin C given in the diet to these mice might have affected their endogenous synthesis of vitamin C, especially at low dose.

278
00:29:28,220 --> 00:29:50,220
And Connie Chow and a number of other people, Ping Loan at the institute looked into that four-linus Polling very carefully and found that, sure enough, when you give small extra doses of vitamin C to mice, you actually decrease the amount of vitamin C in blood and various organs and tissues compared to the mice getting no extra vitamin C.

279
00:29:50,220 --> 00:30:07,220
And you actually have to overcome that by giving much larger amounts of vitamin C. And then you start to see increases in vitamin C in these various tissues and organs and the blood and also protection against the development of skin cancer caused by exposure to ultraviolet light.

280
00:30:07,220 --> 00:30:18,220
So it has nothing to do with people because we don't synthesize vitamin C. So supplemental vitamin C doesn't interfere with anything that we're doing in our livers unlike the mice.

281
00:30:18,220 --> 00:30:28,220
So that argument that Art put forward to explain this problem with Linus Polling didn't seem to hold water to me.

282
00:30:28,220 --> 00:30:44,220
And I looked more carefully at some of the administrative decisions that were being made at that time, specifically with respect to Richard Hicks and affiliation with a group in Santa Cruz, the Hunsburgers, that Polling was not very happy about.

283
00:30:44,220 --> 00:30:55,220
And Hunsburgers were very interested in wheat grass and ebbsisic acid as having cancer prevention or therapeutic properties.

284
00:30:55,220 --> 00:31:05,220
And some experiments along those lines were carried out at the institute where wheat grass was being fed to mice to find out if it could protect them against cancer.

285
00:31:05,220 --> 00:31:19,220
But Polling, I think, and I never talked to him about this, but inferring from what I read, it seemed to me that he was concerned about somewhat flaky character of this operation in Santa Cruz.

286
00:31:19,220 --> 00:31:29,220
And he was worried about a close affiliation because the work that he was already advocating and trying to get funded seemed to be very controversial anyway.

287
00:31:29,220 --> 00:31:42,220
And I don't think he wanted to encourage even more skepticism about the institute's activities by getting associated with fringe or what he might consider fringe organizations.

288
00:31:42,220 --> 00:31:44,220
Robinson had a different perspective.

289
00:31:44,220 --> 00:31:56,220
And also, I think Polling had set up an executive committee composed of himself, Rick Hicks and Art.

290
00:31:56,220 --> 00:32:07,220
And I believe that Art was asked not to make any important decisions without approval of the executive committee.

291
00:32:07,220 --> 00:32:17,220
And Art essentially ignored that and wanted to fire Rick Hicks and Polling like Hicks and thought he was doing a good job.

292
00:32:17,220 --> 00:32:30,220
So I think that the conflict that developed between them had to do with administrative issues, how to run and govern the Linus Plains to Science and Medicine, not scientific issues.

293
00:32:30,220 --> 00:32:35,220
So what did you have a sense of what the conflict was between Robinson and Hicks?

294
00:32:35,220 --> 00:32:47,220
I don't really. I think that Robinson was unhappy with Hicks' performance. And maybe Hicks had not done some things that Robinson expected him to do or had asked him to do.

295
00:32:47,220 --> 00:32:55,220
They also had very different personalities. And there could have been a bit of a personality clash there as well.

296
00:32:55,220 --> 00:33:03,220
So how did the legal brain like to play out Robinson suitings? And that was a multi-year affair?

297
00:33:03,220 --> 00:33:08,220
It was a multi-year affair. It was very distracting to all involve, very expensive proposition.

298
00:33:08,220 --> 00:33:15,220
There were lots of suits. Of course, at that time, I didn't really involve myself with any of that because I had no administrative function.

299
00:33:15,220 --> 00:33:26,220
So I was just happy doing my research and not worrying about what was going on in the legal realm or the administrative hierarchy of the Institute.

300
00:33:26,220 --> 00:33:40,220
But in looking back at these documents retrospectively, it's clear that people were completely subsumed with these legal issues because when these kinds of charges are made and these suits are filed, you really have to do the best you can to protect the organization.

301
00:33:40,220 --> 00:33:50,220
And that means hiring good attorneys and getting into the details of all the issues and countless depositions and document analyses.

302
00:33:50,220 --> 00:34:02,220
And it's all very tedious and very expensive. In a way, it's also quite fascinating because jurisprudence is a very interesting game, legal game that gets played.

303
00:34:02,220 --> 00:34:14,220
And it's interesting to see how the strategies evolve and how the players behave. But it can be incredibly distracting if your main goal is to carry out research.

304
00:34:14,220 --> 00:34:25,220
And I think it was very distracting for everybody involved and art ended up suing his attorneys because he was unhappy with the settlement that had eventually been reached.

305
00:34:26,219 --> 00:34:39,219
And sometime much later, I think between the time I became chief executive officer at Linus Pong's death, art Robinson re-emerged from the past.

306
00:34:39,219 --> 00:34:51,219
And really, I had had nothing to do with him and hadn't heard from him or about him for many, many years because after the settlement in the early 1980s, that was the end of the legal entanglement with art Robinson.

307
00:34:51,219 --> 00:34:59,219
And I knew that he had moved to Oregon to cave junction and set up his own research organization. I wasn't quite sure exactly what he was doing.

308
00:34:59,219 --> 00:35:08,219
This was long before the internet, of course, and it was difficult to fair it out details about people's activities unlike today.

309
00:35:08,219 --> 00:35:15,219
So I really had no reason to think about art Robinson until I got a phone call or a letter.

310
00:35:15,219 --> 00:35:30,219
Actually, it was a letter, I believe, addressed to Linus Pauling from art that Pauling turned over to me that was a request for access to research data that art had generated at the institute before his departure.

311
00:35:30,219 --> 00:35:56,219
So art described this research data as being many filing the five, the steel case five drawer filing cabinets, maybe 10 or 15 of those worth of hard copy paper records that were generated as a result of the metabolic profiling program.

312
00:35:56,219 --> 00:36:03,219
And also very large magnetic data tapes that were maybe a foot in diameter.

313
00:36:03,219 --> 00:36:13,219
And at the time, without going back and actually looking at the terms of the settlement, which of course stipulated that none of that had to be given to art Robinson,

314
00:36:13,219 --> 00:36:23,219
and he'd already been given an opportunity to copy his research data, albeit at high cost before he left the institute, he declined to do so at that time.

315
00:36:23,219 --> 00:36:30,219
But I thought all these years had gone by, there was really nothing to be gained in withholding anything from art Robinson.

316
00:36:30,219 --> 00:36:45,219
And if he was able to translate this raw data into scientific publications that would be scientifically or medically valuable, I was in favor of that.

317
00:36:45,219 --> 00:36:53,219
So I decided to look around and see what I could find that was that resembled what he'd asked for.

318
00:36:53,219 --> 00:37:00,219
And in looking around the institute, I could find nothing that resembled the volume of material that he had requested.

319
00:37:00,219 --> 00:37:05,219
There weren't boxes and boxes or many filing cabinets full of data.

320
00:37:05,219 --> 00:37:11,219
There weren't dozens or hundreds of magnetic data tapes. These things just didn't exist within the building.

321
00:37:11,219 --> 00:37:19,219
So I queried a number of people, including Dick Willoughby, who was our facilities manager, Emil Zucacondle, who had left the institute at that time.

322
00:37:19,219 --> 00:37:25,219
And a number of other people who I thought might have had some knowledge of the whereabouts of this material over time.

323
00:37:25,219 --> 00:37:29,219
No one really seemed to have a clear idea of what had happened to it.

324
00:37:29,219 --> 00:37:35,219
But I reconstructed what I believe to be its disposition.

325
00:37:35,219 --> 00:37:41,219
And I sent this in a letter, Dart Robinson. What I considered a very collegial, cordial letter.

326
00:37:41,219 --> 00:37:45,219
I mean, it was unhappy news for our Robinson, but nevertheless it was as far as I knew.

327
00:37:45,219 --> 00:37:50,219
And as far as I still know, the truth about the disposition of this material.

328
00:37:50,219 --> 00:37:56,219
The institute had a satellite facility on Porter Drive in Stanford, Indutual Park.

329
00:37:56,219 --> 00:38:04,219
And that satellite facility was used for Susa Cala, aging research that was carried out by Jim Fleming and others.

330
00:38:04,219 --> 00:38:19,219
Also, in the 1980s, we had carried out some work on fabricating superconductive material to support one of Pauling's patent application, Stella Kerman, and to some extent, you and Cameron and I worked on that project.

331
00:38:19,219 --> 00:38:24,219
And we also used a number of rooms there for paper storage.

332
00:38:24,219 --> 00:38:33,219
And we'd had problems with the roof leaking in that facility that actually led to a lawsuit with a landlord.

333
00:38:33,219 --> 00:38:40,219
And a lot of the paper that had been stored in that facility was ruined because the leak, the roof leaked.

334
00:38:40,219 --> 00:38:43,219
And the paper was damaged by water.

335
00:38:43,219 --> 00:38:51,219
And I believe that it was just thrown out. And because it was damaged, there wasn't any attempt made to really examine it carefully.

336
00:38:51,219 --> 00:38:54,219
I'm reconstructing that. I don't know that for sure.

337
00:38:54,219 --> 00:39:01,219
But I do know, because I did see it with my own eyes. A lot of destroyed records by water.

338
00:39:01,219 --> 00:39:09,219
And I gave that as what I considered a reasonable explanation of what had happened to our research material.

339
00:39:09,219 --> 00:39:17,219
My understanding was that it had been stored up there because there wasn't any room to really keep it in the 440-page mill road facility.

340
00:39:17,219 --> 00:39:25,219
If, indeed, it had been kept that long, it was at Porter Drive and probably destroyed by water from a leaking roof.

341
00:39:25,219 --> 00:39:33,219
That, as I said, led to litigation with the landlord because the landlord wasn't quick in repairing the roof, unfortunately.

342
00:39:33,219 --> 00:39:45,219
So Art did not take that news very well. And in a way, I can sympathize with it because that work represented a significant percent of his wife's work at that time.

343
00:39:45,219 --> 00:39:54,219
But that's the way it is. The material was gone. It was probably destroyed, probably damaged. And there was nothing to give him.

344
00:39:54,219 --> 00:40:06,219
But he was unwilling to accept that explanation and believed for whatever reason very obscure to me that I must be hiding this material or lying to him, mischaracterizing everything.

345
00:40:06,219 --> 00:40:15,219
And I tried to think about what his motivation for believing that I would do that. And I just could not come up with a sensible motivation.

346
00:40:15,219 --> 00:40:27,219
I think that he played so much emphasis on the importance of this material that it was beyond comprehension to him that it could have been thrown away, even having been damaged.

347
00:40:27,219 --> 00:40:43,219
So he was unwilling to accept that explanation. And that led to kind of a proxy lawsuit against the Institute by a colleague of his, Jane Orient, who I think is associated with him in kind of libertarian politics.

348
00:40:43,219 --> 00:40:54,219
And she's a physician in Arizona, at least at the time, who had made rather strategically, I believe, a small donation to the Institute.

349
00:40:54,219 --> 00:41:03,219
And then later wanted access to research records. And she called me on the telephone and I had a nice conversation with her and she was asking about research.

350
00:41:03,219 --> 00:41:14,219
And at first I was confused. I thought she was talking about the protein profiling work. And then I realized that she was talking about the metabolic profiling work.

351
00:41:14,219 --> 00:41:27,219
And I talked about some of the work that had been ongoing until the mid 1980s and so forth. And the development of the apparatus and data collection and analysis and loss of funding and so forth.

352
00:41:27,219 --> 00:41:39,219
And I came clear that what she was really interested in was this old art robins in the material. And I think at the time I told her the same thing I told art, which is I don't know what happened to it. We don't have it.

353
00:41:39,219 --> 00:41:49,219
So I can't offer it to you. So that led to a suit that she filed against the Institute for access to this publicly financed research data.

354
00:41:49,219 --> 00:42:00,219
That of course involved a lot of time and energy and resources, but eventually was dismissed by the court for lack of standing essentially.

355
00:42:00,219 --> 00:42:07,219
Do you have a sense of was it a brain sort of reconciliation involved in the following diet?

356
00:42:07,219 --> 00:42:24,219
Well, I think arts letter to Linus Pauling and Linus Pauling's response to him if there was a response was cordial. Arts letter was pretty cordial. So I don't know that they communicated much from the time the lawsuit finished until that letter in the early 1990s.

357
00:42:24,219 --> 00:42:37,219
My guess is they probably did not because art really in many at many occasions have lots of bad things to say about the Institute and Linus Pauling. So I can't imagine that they really communicated much.

358
00:42:37,219 --> 00:42:53,219
And I don't know that that was arts attempt reconciliation or whether he viewed that opportunity of me being in charge in the Institute now and Pauling gradually expiring as an opportunity to

359
00:42:53,219 --> 00:43:00,219
get access to research data that he thought we've been sitting on all those years.

360
00:43:00,219 --> 00:43:14,219
Okay, well we switched to you in Cameron. He arrived in 1978 perhaps in a full time capacity of mental risk. But did you recall your first impressions of Cameron?

361
00:43:14,219 --> 00:43:28,219
Cameron was a wonderful person. He was very charming. He had a great sense of humor. He also had the Scottish brogue and was shy I think.

362
00:43:28,219 --> 00:43:39,219
He didn't like to talk in public and sometimes it was hard to understand what he was saying because of his accent and a tendency a bit to mumble sometimes.

363
00:43:39,219 --> 00:43:53,219
But he was very intelligent, very compassionate. Clearly a research-minded physician who was interested in finding new ways to help his patients live with cancer.

364
00:43:53,219 --> 00:44:05,219
I think he and Pauling initially thought that vitamin C might be able to turn cancer into a manageable disease, a chronic disease rather than something that would kill you in short order.

365
00:44:05,219 --> 00:44:13,219
And that led him to consider vitamin C as having potential value and treating cancer patients. I really enjoyed him.

366
00:44:13,219 --> 00:44:26,219
I would go to parties with him quite often. He loved to drink single malt scotch which he would bring from every time he went to Scotland and came back he would always have him.

367
00:44:26,219 --> 00:44:33,219
It seemed like an arm-load of single malt scotches for everyone to try. And he liked to smoke cigarettes too.

368
00:44:33,219 --> 00:44:45,219
Which was a bit ironic. Sometimes it's the old do as I say, but not as I do motif that you see sometimes with physicians or other people.

369
00:44:45,219 --> 00:44:54,219
Cameron was not pious. He didn't preach to people about what they should or shouldn't do. And he was well aware of his own bad habit of smoking.

370
00:44:54,219 --> 00:45:07,219
He was hard to reconcile with his career as a cancer surgeon, removing disease lungs and other tissue from patients. But nevertheless he found it very difficult to quit.

371
00:45:07,219 --> 00:45:12,219
I know he tried to quit smoking a number of times but didn't succeed.

372
00:45:12,219 --> 00:45:24,219
So I kind of liked him because he had some weaknesses as well. But he was extremely bright and very compassionate person.

373
00:45:24,219 --> 00:45:28,219
And in party settings he was more socialized.

374
00:45:28,219 --> 00:45:30,219
And in his party settings he was more social.

375
00:45:30,219 --> 00:45:37,219
Yeah he was very social. Very very social. My girlfriend and I loved to hear him tell tales about his work in Burma.

376
00:45:37,219 --> 00:45:48,219
I remember one story he told about lancing a boil on an elephant which was quite extraordinary.

377
00:45:48,219 --> 00:46:01,219
And he told me about some of the therapy available to the cohort of cancer patients that he was treating which was called Brompton's cocktail which was a mixture of I believe alcohol, cocaine and heroin.

378
00:46:01,219 --> 00:46:10,219
