415
00:50:57,219 --> 00:51:05,219
So that was abandoned and that was set up by John Catchpool. And like I said, it didn't last very long.

416
00:51:05,219 --> 00:51:25,219
So we were struggling at the time between giving sensible, practical and non-medical advice to people because Cameron wasn't licensed to practice medicine in the United States, so he couldn't give medical advice to people.

417
00:51:25,219 --> 00:51:38,219
So we had to be a bit oblique about it and provide patients and their physicians with research papers and allude to responses of other similar patients to a certain course of therapy and so forth.

418
00:51:38,219 --> 00:51:52,219
So Cameron was working very hard to kind of perfect our strategy of responding to the public for these health related questions so that we didn't incur legal liability,

419
00:51:52,219 --> 00:52:05,219
but we were acting ethically and morally and trying to be good citizens and compassionate because many of the people who contacted the Institute in those days were in dire straits.

420
00:52:05,219 --> 00:52:14,219
These were people for whom traditional conventional therapy was not successful and they were just waiting to die and they weren't willing to accept that fate.

421
00:52:14,219 --> 00:52:25,219
So they were turning to other modalities which included things like vitamin C and once they started to consider that naturally the tendency was to get in touch with the Institute and talk to you and Cameron.

422
00:52:25,219 --> 00:52:35,219
So he spent an enormous amount of time on the phone and writing letters to cancer patients and other people with questions about vitamin C.

423
00:52:35,219 --> 00:52:45,219
Well, Cameron and Pauline's research on cancer attracted a great deal of criticism and do you have a sense of how they respond internally?

424
00:52:45,219 --> 00:53:02,219
Yeah, I think they felt and this has been written about many times and I think you can infer their emotions from some of the letters that appeared in journals and elsewhere that they'd been treated badly by the male clinic.

425
00:53:03,219 --> 00:53:13,219
Both Cameron and Pauline were astonished to find out and angry that the male clinic researchers Craig and Mortel had never even read Cameron's papers, relevant papers.

426
00:53:13,219 --> 00:53:30,219
So they ostensibly were charged by the NCI with replicating Cameron's work yet they knew virtually nothing about it and had they read Cameron's papers they may have noticed that Cameron was giving high dose vitamin C both orally and intravenously.

427
00:53:30,219 --> 00:53:45,219
And that as it turns out may have been a very crucial feature that was completely ignored by them because they perhaps had too much ubrous to read this Scottish surgeon's papers on vitamin C and cancer.

428
00:53:45,219 --> 00:54:14,219
And I think the fact that the studies were published without the courtesy of showing the study before publication to Pauline and Cameron did not sit well with them because once the study was published immediately the media wants responses the same day and it put you in an awkward position because Cameron Pauline had that a time to really read the study and think about it carefully and come up with a cogent analysis and critique of it.

429
00:54:14,219 --> 00:54:23,219
So they were angered by that as well because they felt that professional courtesy was not extended to them in that regard.

430
00:54:23,219 --> 00:54:40,219
And they felt that the work that the male clinic had done was to use Pauline's word somewhat fraudulent and they were worried that this would end serious consideration of vitamin C as a junk to therapy for cancer.

431
00:54:40,219 --> 00:54:53,219
And they felt that that would be unethical and immoral and unscientific and ill conceived so they were upset and it was clear that they were upset.

432
00:54:53,219 --> 00:55:16,219
But Cameron, neither Cameron or Pauline were, they didn't reveal anger, they didn't shout or break things or storm around or anything like that but voices were raised definitely and Cameron was not very pleased by the work that had been done at the male clinic.

433
00:55:16,219 --> 00:55:19,219
It showed.

434
00:55:19,219 --> 00:55:25,219
How much of the staff, what was the reaction to the criticism of the agencies have?

435
00:55:25,219 --> 00:55:45,219
I think everyone was unhappy and angry as well. I think everyone shared the anger that these studies had been published and they weren't carefully done and there seemed to be lots of problems with them that they didn't replicate Cameron's protocol or Cameron's work as they were purportedly did.

436
00:55:45,219 --> 00:56:00,219
I think there was also concern among the fundraising staff that this might bode ill for continuing efforts to raise money to support research at the institute and sure enough, there were some fundraising problems after that that work was published.

437
00:56:01,219 --> 00:56:24,219
So it had a big impact on our work at the institute as well as sort of shelving serious consideration of vitamin C and cancer for many, many years which I think was a real disservice to the research community and to the huge population of cancer patients out there who might have benefited from this had the research been done more carefully early on.

438
00:56:25,219 --> 00:56:30,219
But the staff continued to believe in the scientific ways of the idea.

439
00:56:30,219 --> 00:56:40,219
Yes. And I think partly because the arguments that both Cameron and Pauline loved the leveled against the male clinic researchers were very cogent and sensible.

440
00:56:40,219 --> 00:56:45,219
They weren't just fringe arguments that had no validity.

441
00:56:45,219 --> 00:56:52,219
They were valid arguments and I think everyone was well aware of them.

442
00:56:52,219 --> 00:57:08,219
In Cameron I think Cameron made, I think he said one time that at first he thought they were just dealing with fools and then he realized they were dealing with naves as he put it.

443
00:57:08,219 --> 00:57:18,219
You mentioned very briefly in 1970 if the clinic had a risk that the cancer would set up a clinic for diagnosing and treating disease as it must have long been possible.

444
00:57:18,219 --> 00:57:24,219
Well it predated my arrival at the institute so I don't really have a lot of firsthand knowledge about the clinic.

445
00:57:24,219 --> 00:57:34,219
I know that the concept there was clear that some people might benefit from orthomolecular medical treatment.

446
00:57:34,219 --> 00:57:47,219
But I think the funding and liability issues were, the funding was too low and the liability issues were too great to really turn that into a practical functional concern.

447
00:57:47,219 --> 00:58:01,219
And I do remember Kareen Gorham and others telling me that there were people who showed up knocking on the door, Deathly Ill, and spent their last money on a bus ticket to get there and had no money and expected to be cured.

448
00:58:01,219 --> 00:58:06,219
And that was not uncommon and that of course just was not possible.

449
00:58:06,219 --> 00:58:16,219
So I think rather than risk having the tail wag the dog they decided to dissolve the clinic rather quickly.

