00:59:06,219 --> 00:59:11,219
I can't remember those discussions very carefully now though.

462
00:59:11,219 --> 00:59:22,219
Well we talked about this kind of off the line throughout the interview but I'm wondering if you could give a little bit more on the kind of the chronic money problems that you've had since you've faced for a very long time.

463
00:59:22,219 --> 00:59:31,219
Yeah well the institute was I think founded and moved off the campus of Stanford University initially because there wasn't enough money.

464
00:59:31,219 --> 00:59:40,219
Nor was there enough space at Stanford to carry out the work that Pauling really felt would make a big impact in public health, namely research and orthomolecular medicine.

465
00:59:40,219 --> 00:59:43,219
Specifically research on vitamin C.

466
00:59:43,219 --> 00:59:52,219
And I think Pauling and Robinson felt that this had great potential as did the metabolite profiling metabolic profiling program.

467
00:59:52,219 --> 01:00:02,219
So they moved, they founded the institute, moved to this location that we've talked about in Menlo Park and then set about trying to raise money to carry out this research.

468
01:00:02,219 --> 01:00:13,219
And government grants were not forthcoming for the vitamin C work although the metabolite metabolic profiling work was supported to a large extent by government grants in those days.

469
01:00:13,219 --> 01:00:22,219
The development of the apparatus, data analysis, data collection, sample collection, things like that.

470
01:00:23,219 --> 01:00:45,219
And then as the institute started to grow the need for more resources, financial resources became pretty clear and that's when art Robinson and Rick Hicks got involved in this direct mail solicitation program because they correctly perceived that the public had responded to Pauling's message and thoughts about vitamin C and health.

471
01:00:45,219 --> 01:01:04,219
Much more quickly than the medical community and the scientific community. So there were lots of people out there who believed that Pauling was right about vitamin C and wanted to sort of support the David versus the Goliath, Pauling versus the Convention, the Convention on Medical Establishment.

472
01:01:04,219 --> 01:01:26,219
So they were willing to give small and large donations to support research at the institute. So in a way that was very good because it allowed the institute to hire staff scientists without tenure of course but hire them and provide them with money to carry out research that was not dependent on government grants or corporate sponsorship.

473
01:01:26,219 --> 01:01:33,219
Although throughout the history of the institute, corporate sponsorship and contracts were quite variable.

474
01:01:33,219 --> 01:01:52,219
The Hoffman-LaRose gave money, the Japan Shipbuilding Industry Foundation gave money. So there were corporate and organizational sources of funding for the institute but sometimes they were restricted and sometimes they were non-restricted.

475
01:01:52,219 --> 01:02:01,219
Luckily the money from some of those large donors was unrestricted and could be applied across the board to support whatever line is Pauling.

476
01:02:01,219 --> 01:02:07,219
Art Robins and Ray Neel Zucicondle felt was important.

477
01:02:07,219 --> 01:02:27,219
But because of, excuse me, because of the stock market performance and the vagaries of the national economy over years that affected the ability of individuals to some extent corporations to give money.

478
01:02:27,219 --> 01:02:37,219
It affected their philanthropic abilities. So when there were down times during recessions and other down times people gave less money.

479
01:02:37,219 --> 01:02:56,219
Nevertheless, at the institute the costs were constant or increasing. So in those times there was always a pinch. And that would often be resolved transiently by decreasing contributions to pension plans or salary reductions that were temporary.

480
01:02:56,219 --> 01:03:07,219
So they would be lifted once the economic picture brightens somewhat. So it was always kind of a roller coaster depending upon what was going on in the national economy.

481
01:03:07,219 --> 01:03:20,219
Because when you're a charitable organization depending upon the philanthropy of others, the economic climate affects the ability to give. And we certainly were aware of that.

482
01:03:20,219 --> 01:03:36,219
Later, as I said, when the Mayo Clinic studies on vitamin C and cancer were published, that also caused transient loss in funds available to the institute because people were giving less money because they felt now vitamin C had failed to show anything.

483
01:03:36,219 --> 01:04:03,219
Why support that kind of research? And still later when people became aware of Pauling's interest in work in HIV infection, AIDS, and vitamin C, that also caused transient loss in support because some people were opposed to that work on moral grounds and didn't want to see that kind of research funded at the institute.

484
01:04:03,219 --> 01:04:13,219
And it strikes me that there couldn't have been many organizations like LDSM, where scientific research that were within the event there weren't funds for it.

485
01:04:13,219 --> 01:04:28,219
