01:04:28,219 --> 01:04:35,219
So impact factors can be calculated for journals, they can be calculated for scientists, they can also be calculated for institutions.

487
01:04:35,219 --> 01:04:48,219
And I believe the result of John's analysis at that time ranked the institute in the top 15 nonprofit biomedical research institutes in the country on the basis of impact factor.

488
01:04:48,219 --> 01:04:58,219
And I should add that that was not all related to Linus Pauling's productivity. Lots of papers from institute staff figured in the calculation of the impact factor.

489
01:04:58,219 --> 01:05:09,219
So despite the fact that there were financial problems throughout the institute's career, I think ultimately in terms of productivity and influence, I think it succeeded.

